Documents the full compile pipeline from `dict.steno` to the four `out/` artifacts (`plain.json`, `smart.json`, `plover-keys.json`, `snippets.json`), and is the canonical description of pass ordering, the editor model, and the error taxonomy — treat it as the source of truth to update whenever pass boundaries, `Behaviors` presets, or error types change in the code it describes.

The pipeline is strictly one-way: `parse` → Pass A (`expand/counts.rs`) → Pass B (`expand/append.rs`, `types.rs`) → line-flag (`expand/lineflag.rs`) → renderers (`render/plain.rs`, `render/smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`). `expand_dict` in `expand/mod.rs` runs Pass A, Pass B, and line-flag in one call; all three binaries call it and hand the resulting `Vec<TypedEntry>` to a renderer. After Pass A, no `Repeat`/`Dcount`/`Computed` chunks remain. `@count` with no count operator (or vice versa) is a parse-time error. Pass B never emits `@type` entries on their own — they're consumed into the append set — and `@fuse` merges the shape's last stroke segment into the first appended type stroke so no type-less intermediate stroke is ever required. `TypedEntry` tracks terminal vs. non-terminal (type-append intermediate) status plus the source `Entry` for flag lookups later.

The module dependency direction is an explicit invariant: `render`/`snippet`/`blocks` depend on `expand`, which depends on `parse` and `stroke`; `json_out` is a leaf used only at emission; nothing lower depends on anything higher. Only the three binaries write files — the library (`lib.rs`) exposes every stage but performs no I/O itself.

The editor model (`editor/`) is three functions — `interpret(events, behaviors) -> EditorState`, `movement_events(buffer, from, to) -> Event[]`, `serialize(events) -> String` — and every rendering "profile" is just a `Behaviors` preset (`auto_close`, `type_over`, `auto_indent`): `PLAIN` (all off, cursor walks back from doc end), `SMART` (auto_close+type_over on, drops the trailing run of auto-closers), `SMART_INDENT` (adds auto_indent, needed for multi-level `@literal` blocks). Tests assert `interpret(emit(t, B), B)` round-trips for each profile — the editor is simulated, never actually executed. `%0`'s landing position is tracked via `Mark(n)` events and named `target` in `EditorState`.

Five error types, one per pass, none swallowed: `StenoError` (parse; carries 1-based line, and column for template errors), `StrokeError` (stroke arithmetic), `ExpandError` (Pass A/B; wraps `StrokeError` via `From`), `RenderError`, `SnippetError` (both: unresolved chunk reaching that stage, or impossible movement). Output files are written only after `build_dict`'s collision check (same stroke, different value) passes — so a caller never gets partial silent output.

Companion doc `steno-format.md` specifies the source syntax parsed by `parse/`; this file assumes that syntax as given and focuses on what happens to it after parsing.